THE ANC says it will have to teach youth league members the difference between emotions and politics after they nearly killed each other during a shoot-out at a meeting.Six of the eight ANCYL members who were shot during the tense meeting on Saturday were released from hospital on Monday.The six men, aged between 25 and 34, were discharged from Mount Ayliff Hospital, while two others are reportedly in a stable condition.An injured security guard was transferred to Nelson Mandela Academic Hospital in Mthatha in a critical condition.Oscar Mabuyane, ANC provincial secretary, promised the party would take action as soon as they received a report on what led to the violence at the meeting in Mount Ayliff.&ldquo;The ANC strongly condemns any act of violence within the organisation. &ldquo;We have come to realise the need to educate our members so they learn the difference between emotions and politics.Provincial health spokesman Sizwe Kupelo said the injured security guard suffered serious injuries to the upper body but was in a stable condition.One of the survivors, Sindile Phakathi (30), told the SunTeam of his ordeal.&ldquo;I ran as soon as I heard gunshots. &ldquo;Next thing I knew, I was lying on the floor and then I woke up at hospital. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve just been discharged and I&rsquo;m feeling much better,&rdquo; he said.Colonel Nomazwi Nkombisa, acting cluster commander at Mount Ayliff, said police are still investigating the shooting. No arrests have yet been made.